## **1\. Defining Product Sense**

Two of the best explanations of product sense I’ve seen are from Sid Arora and Shreyas Doshi.

Let’s take a look at each.

Here’s [Sid’s](https://www.justanotherpm.com/blog/product-sense-what-is-it-and-how-can-you-improve-it):

![diagram][image1]

Sid defines product sense as the ability to take a vague and ambiguous problem statement, take it through user, problem, and solution discovery, deploy the solution, and measure results.

Now let’s look at Shreyas’ [definition](https://maven.com/shreyas-doshi/product-sense):

![A view of everything we will cover in this course. This course material isn't available anywhere else.][image2]

Shreyas doesn’t per se define it. He identifies levers of improving your product sense as: motivation theory, cognitive empathy, creativity, domain expertise, and communication.

What you can see from both of these is that **they are very broad definitions** both of what product sense is, and how you can improve it.

Product sense is not a small topic. It’s **basically all of the product thinking a PM needs to do**.

We can *formally define* it as:

*Product sense is the ability to make consistently good product decisions; knowing what to build, for whom, and why. It’s pattern recognition across user needs, market dynamics, and execution tradeoffs*

*Now, let’s move on to AI product sense…*

## **2\. Defining AI Product Sense**

When I was a VP of Product at Apollo.io ($2.5B Sales Tech SaaS), we built an AI email writer.

The demo was perfect. Our CEO, Tim, who had a notoriously high bar, actually loved it. The model responses were great. As were the interface and marketing material.

The sales team jumped at selling it.

Three weeks later, **it was dead**.

Users sometimes loved the emails. Other times, it destroyed their spam rating and tanked their inbox. Trust was being evaporated. And it was costing us an arm and a leg.

So we paused that version of the feature. $1.2M of development seemingly *wasted* (3 months of the 5 people building it).

That was when I learned the invisible line that separates product sense and **AI product sense**. Traditional product sense failed us in the AI scenario:

1. The models in AI were non-deterministic  
2. And the costs weren’t fixed

These distinctions make **AI product sense its own skill**, unique from product sense.

So how do we define AI product sense? In plain english:

![][image3]

More formally:

*AI Product Sense is the fit between **need**, **model behavior**, and the **economic envelope** that lets that behavior repeatedly deliver value under uncertainty.*

Here’s what I mean.

At Apollo, when we came back and tweaked everything:

* The underlying context engineering  
* The economics of the models we were using  
* The feedback loop that we were getting from users

We ended up shipping the highly successful email writer you see in the product today (which drove millions in revenue).

![Pick an email address.][image4]

You **need to have** a *highly tuned* AI product sense to avoid those wasted development cycles, and ship features that land the first time.

As [Marty Cagan](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J0FOFJFtOFw) [says](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UvemAAB0ies&feature=youtu.be), it’s something you **can** and **need** to improve.

After working on 100s of AI features across the two of us, we’ve realized that great AI product sense is about training yourself to see through five specific lenses simultaneously.

We call theam **REALM** (so you can remember them):

![][image5]

When you build without one of these lenses, your product is blind. It might look shiny on the surface, but it won’t stand up in the real world.

*And you’re left with the nightmare scenario we began with.*

But when you learn to build *with* all five, you stop guessing. *You start seeing the system as it really is, not as you wish it to be.*

And this leads to product success.

When a team’s product sense is strong:

* Users *forgive* occasional imperfections because the experience still feels coherent  
* Costs stay under control because you’re not fighting physics  
* Your product doesn’t just work, it earns the right to scale  
* Trust compounds over time

Think about [ChatGPT](https://www.news.aakashg.com/p/chatgpt-for-pms). There might be the occasional imperfection. But users forgive the occasional imperfections. Trust compounds over time. And the business is scaling in a way that costs are kept under control.

**That’s product sense in action**.

## **4\. The 10 Core Principles Through the REALM Lenses**

Most AI products won’t fail because of technology.

They will fail because they were designed with a **deterministic mindset in a probabilistic world**.

PMs treat AI features like checkboxes: “does it generate text?” “Does it answer the query?” “Does it return an image?”.

But the real craft isn’t in making the model do something; *it’s in shaping the experience around its inherent unpredictability* so that users experience it as stable, trustworthy, and even magical.

That shaping happens through 10 core principles, organized across the five REALM lenses. When you build without one of these lenses, your product is blind. But when you learn to build with all five, you stop guessing and start seeing *the system as it really is*.

Let’s go deep on each lens and its principles…

![][image6]

### **REALITY: Understanding True User Needs and Model Behavior**

The Reality lens asks: Are you building for *the world as it actually is*, or as you wish it to be?

Most AI products fail here first. They’re built on assumptions about user needs that don’t hold up, or expectations about model behavior that ignore the probabilistic nature of AI.

#### **Principle 1 \- Probabilistic Fit, Not Feature Fit**

In a traditional product, when you ship a feature, you expect it to behave the same way every time. But with AI, no two outputs are exactly the same… and *that’s where most PMs lose control*.

If you judge your AI product purely on whether it works in one or two demos, you’ll fool yourself into thinking you’ve nailed it. But your users will live in the messy reality of **P50, P80, P95 performance**.

That’s why the real question isn’t “Does it work?” but **“How does it behave across a distribution of real inputs, and can the experience absorb the variance without breaking trust?”**

This is where the concept of a **Quality Envelope** comes in.

When building an AI product, define three performance percentiles upfront:

* **P50**: The experience *half of users* should consistently get. The median, the “everyday” baseline.  
* **P80**: The experience *the majority* should feel when the system works well… not rare, but noticeably strong.  
* **P95**: The “delight zone”, the *rare but remarkable* outputs that make people tweet about your product, talk about it in meetings, or tell a friend.

But… and this is crucial… you should also define what’s unacceptable. This is your **Tolerance of Wrongness**: the types of errors the product can survive, and the types it *absolutely cannot*.

For example, a writing assistant can survive a slightly awkward sentence but *not* a fabricated quote. A healthcare triage system can survive a spelling error but *not* a misclassification of severity.

And once this Quality Envelope and Tolerance of Wrongness are clear, **the UX becomes the shock absorber**. You design the experience so that *misses don’t feel like betrayals*. Maybe that means surfacing confidence levels, maybe it means quick correction flows, maybe it means fallback modes… but either way, you stop pretending the model is perfect, and start shaping the experience so users trust it anyway.

This is how you build AI that doesn’t collapse under its own unpredictability.

#### **Principle 2 \- Design for Variance**

Every AI product has variance. The difference between good and great PMs is that great PMs *design around that variance intentionally*.

You can’t eliminate variance (it’s fundamental to how AI works). But you can shape the experience so variance becomes a feature, not a bug.

**Four patterns that turn unpredictable behavior into usable, lovable experiences:**

1. **Preview-Then-Prove**: Give users a fast preview (Spark), then *quietly verify* key claims or details in the background before they commit. Users feel speed without sacrificing trust.  
2. **Confidence-Forward**: Only surface model confidence when it *changes the user’s decision*, not as vanity metrics. Confidence should be actionable, not decorative.  
3. **Correct-Without-Penalty**: Make correction frictionless. Don’t punish the user for the model’s mistakes. *One click* to refine, fix, or tighten… without redoing everything.  
4. **Recover-With-Humility**: When the model fails, acknowledge the limitation explicitly, and offer a graceful fallback. Don’t gaslight the user with fake certainty. *Humble systems are more trusted than arrogant ones*.

#### **Principle 3 \- The Data Nutrition Label**

Users don’t trust black boxes. If they can’t see what’s under the hood, they’ll hesitate. And that hesitation *kills adoption faster than any technical failure*.

Focus on **making uncertainty legible** rather than overwhelming users with technical details.

Think about nutrition labels on food. They show you *exactly what you’re consuming* in terms you can understand. Simple, transparent, trustworthy.

AI products need the same thing. **Where did this information come from? How current is it? What does the system know it doesn’t know?**

When ChatGPT tells you its knowledge cutoff, that’s a nutrition label. When GitHub Copilot shows you which repo a suggestion came from, *that’s a nutrition label*.

Users will forgive imperfections when they understand the boundaries. But they’ll abandon products that feel like they’re hiding something.

### **ELASTICITY: Managing Model Behavior Under Variance**

The Elasticity lens asks: How does your product behave when conditions *stretch, scale, or shift*?

This is where most demos break. Everything looks perfect under controlled conditions, but **real users bring chaos**: edge cases, unexpected inputs, scale that exposes brittleness.

#### **Principle 4 \- Context Is Capital**

Every bit of context you pass into a model (the user’s intent, their history, their environment, relevant knowledge, previous actions) *shrinks variance and amplifies relevance*. But it also costs money and adds latency. **That’s why great AI PMs manage context like a budget.**

Use the **Context Ledger**.

1. On the *Asset* side, list every piece of context that can make the model smarter: user profile, task-specific examples, structured data, domain constraints, retrieved docs, active session state.  
2. On the *Debit* side, list the real-world costs of that context: token cost, serialization time, staleness risk, privacy risk, legal exposure.  
3. And in the *Profit* column, measure **variance reduction** (i.e., how much fewer errors or corrections happen when that piece of context is included).  
4. Then carve out a **Minimal Golden Context (MGC)**: the *smallest, sharpest* set of context that reliably moves the needle for this task. Not everything you can stuff in. Just the pieces that truly matter.  
5. From there, layer on **Adaptive Context Accrual**: dynamically pulling in *more* context only when the user’s task, or the model’s confidence, actually demands it.  
6. And finally, set **Context Freshness SLAs**: clear rules for *how often* different pieces of context must be updated, re-validated, or thrown away. Because stale context is often *worse than no context at all*.

Why does this matter? Because uncontrolled context is the fastest way to destroy your margins and your latency. But disciplined context turns good models into great experiences.

#### **Principle 5 \- The Latency Envelope**

Latency isn’t just an engineering metric. **Latency is a psychological experience**.

A two-second delay in a web form and a two-second delay in a creative ideation flow *feel completely different*. The same number on a dashboard has radically different meanings depending on user expectations, task urgency, and interaction design.

That’s why you should use the **Spark / Shape / Seal** framework to design around latency:

**Spark (0.3–0.7s)**: The very first signal to the user that the system is alive, listening, and already making progress. This could be an outline, a header, a partial preview, or even a well-designed loading skeleton with meaningful hints. Spark is about *psychological trust* (”Okay, it’s working”).

**Shape (1–2.5s)**: A first useful structure. Not perfect, but *structured enough* that the user can start reacting, editing, or steering. This is where most of the UX magic happens. If you give users something they can work with early, latency becomes less painful.

**Seal (≤7s)**: The final, polished output or clear path to a completed action. Seal is where confidence, verification, and actionability meet.

When you break your interaction into Spark, Shape, and Seal, latency stops feeling like “waiting” and starts feeling like *progress*.

#### **Principle 6 \- Agent Choreography, Not Agent Hype**

“AI agents” are one of the most abused buzzwords right now. But underneath the noise, there’s a quiet truth: agents are only useful when they are *choreographed over brittle edges with clear boundaries*.

Define the building blocks:

* **Task**: atomic steps that can be executed and evaluated cleanly.  
* **Edge**: the boundaries where action becomes risky (e.g., sending emails, deleting data, making payments).  
* **Guard**: the specific policies, checks, or human approvals required to cross those edges.

And then make sure you can trust it using the **Human-in-the-Loop Ladder**:

* **Suggest**: agent *proposes* a sequence with reasons.  
* **Simulate**: agent runs in a sandbox and shows diffs.  
* **Supervise**: agent acts with micro-approvals.  
* **Safeguarded Autonomy**: agent acts within strict guardrails and escalates outside them.

This ladder gives structure to what most teams treat as chaos. Instead of jumping to full autonomy and hoping for the best, *you earn each rung with evidence*. That’s how you build trust with both users and your own engineering team.

### **AFFORDABILITY: Keeping Economics Sustainable**

The Affordability lens asks: Can the economics of your product actually support the value you’re delivering?

Most AI demos are economically fraudulent. They look perfect in controlled environments. Then you scale to real traffic and realize *you’re burning money faster than you’re creating value*.

#### **Principle 7 \- Economics Before Elegance**

Every AI flow has a cost structure that’s mostly invisible until it’s too late. There’s the cost to acquire context, generate outputs, verify accuracy, and handle *the error tax* when things go wrong.

If your demo costs $47 per user action and your revenue per user is $12, you don’t have a product. You have an expensive science project that dies when the CFO starts asking questions.

**Economics isn’t something you optimize later. It’s a constraint you design within from day one.**

Here’s what disciplined cost management looks like:

* Track **cost per outcome**, not cost per call. A single expensive call that solves the problem completely is better than five cheap calls that leave the user stuck.  
* Build **cost escape valves**: clear points where the system can gracefully degrade to cheaper approaches without destroying the experience.  
* Know your **economic ceiling**: the maximum you can spend per user action while still maintaining healthy unit economics.  
* And measure **value velocity**: how quickly users get to an outcome they’d actually pay for, relative to what you’re spending to get them there.

When you design with economics upfront, you build products that can *actually scale*.

### **LIABILITY: Building and Maintaining Trust**

The Liability lens asks: What happens when things go wrong, and how do you protect trust?

Trust is the currency of AI products. Users won’t adopt systems they don’t trust. And trust, once broken, is nearly impossible to rebuild.

#### **Principle 8 \- Evals as a Product**

Most teams treat evals like a QA checklist. Run them once, check the accuracy number, call it done.

That’s not how AI works. **Your model drifts. Edge cases appear. The outputs that worked last month quietly degrade this month.**

Evals serve as *the living nervous system of your product*, monitoring continuously rather than checking once.

The best AI PMs check them weekly and ask **“How is it failing?”** They measure whether quality holds at real serving costs and whether errors are acceptable or catastrophic.

Here’s the truth: accuracy is a vanity metric. What matters is *wrongness*. A writing assistant that occasionally uses a clunky phrase is tolerable. One that fabricates quotes is not.

#### **Principle 9 \- The UMD Contract (User–Model–Data)**

Every great AI product has a hidden contract that governs how power flows between the user, the model, and the data.

Make that contract explicit.

**User** provides intent, goals, context, and approval power.  
**Model** provides reasoning under stated limits, confidence signals, and refusal behaviors.  
**Data** provides structure, provenance, and freshness.

When these roles are clear, confusion disappears. When they’re not, *users blame the wrong actor and trust evaporates quietly*.

### **MARKET: Creating Compounding Advantage**

The Market lens asks: Why can’t someone copy this in three months?

Anyone can copy your AI feature. What they can’t copy is *the moment you own in a user’s workflow*.

#### **Principle 10 \- The SUQS Metric Set**

Finally, if you can’t measure the experience, you can’t improve it.

Traditional metrics like clicks or NPS are too shallow for AI products. That’s why you should aim for **SUQS** as your core operating dashboard:

**S** (Speed): Time to First Value (Spark) and Time to Seal (final output).  
**U** (Usefulness): Edit distance, replay rate, task completion velocity.  
**Q** (Quality): Acceptance rate, verified success rate.  
**S** (Safety): Intervention rate, risk breaches prevented.

These metrics guide you through a probabilistic landscape. When SUQS improves, *users trust more*. When SUQS drifts, everything else eventually breaks.

The best part? SUQS compounds. Every improvement in Speed makes users try more tasks. Every gain in Quality increases their willingness to trust the system with harder problems. Every Safety win builds permission for more autonomy.

This is how AI products scale: not through viral growth tactics, but through *trust that compounds over time*.

When you internalize all 10 principles across the REALM lenses, something shifts. You stop reacting to model behavior and start *designing systems that absorb unpredictability gracefully*. You stop guessing about trust and start building it deliberately.

That’s AI Product Sense in action.

But understanding these principles once isn’t enough. **AI products drift**. Models change. User expectations evolve. Edge cases emerge. The feature that worked beautifully in March might quietly degrade by June.

You need a deliberate rhythm to keep your product sense sharp and your systems improving.

## **5\. Feedback Loops & Learning Systems**

A traditional SaaS product can run on stable behavior for years. Buttons don’t change their minds. Forms don’t decide to output something different every Tuesday. But AI is different:

* Your model drifts.  
* Your users change their behavior as they learn what the system can and can’t do.  
* Your cost structure shifts as you optimize.  
* Your trust dynamics evolve with usage.

So, if your product isn’t built on **structured, deliberate feedback loops**, you’re not managing an AI system, you’re just *hoping* it behaves.

Great AI PMs build their products like living organisms: constantly sensing, adjusting, learning, and tightening. And for that, use a simple but powerful loop Miqdad developed called **SPLIT**.

SPLIT stands for: **S**ense → **P**robe → **L**earn → **I**ntegrate → **T**rack.

It’s a weekly rhythm. A tight loop. A compounding engine. Let’s break it down:

![][image7]

OpenAI uses this loop to great effect.

Steal it.

With this loop in place, there are a few deadly **anti-patterns** to be aware of that OpenAI has seen over time.

These will quietly eat your product alive if left unchecked.

1. **The Wizard Trap**  
   You’ve seen this. The demo works perfectly because it’s handcrafted for the happy path. But as soon as real users hit it, everything collapses. Why? Because no one ever sensed or tracked the tail ends of the distribution. Wizard Traps look magical on stage and die quietly in production.  
2. **Feature Fog**  
   This happens when a team keeps layering knobs and toggles on top of variance instead of reducing the variance itself. Every new knob feels like “control,” but in reality, you’re just giving users the burden of managing model behavior that *you* should have absorbed.  
3. **Data Drizzle**  
   Teams panic when outputs degrade and respond by dumping *more* context into prompts. It feels like fixing the problem… but it’s actually making the system slower, costlier, and more fragile. This happens when there’s no Context Ledger discipline.  
4. **Latency Debt**  
   The slow creep. You add a few verifications here, a few extra retrieval steps there. Spark slips from 0.6s to 1.2s. Shape stretches from 2s to 4\. Suddenly, everything *feels* slower, even if outputs are “better.” Without tracking Spark/Shape/Seal envelopes, latency debt builds quietly and kills trust.

Learn from the mistakes\!

## **6\. System Design for AI Product Sense**

Up to this point, we’ve talked about how great AI products are *perceived*: the clarity of the foundation, the core principles that shape experience, and the feedback loops that let them learn.

But now we step behind the curtain.

Because beneath every AI product that feels fast, reliable, and smart, there’s an **invisible system design** that quietly makes that magic possible:a system that understands context, choreographs models, caches intelligently, routes with intent, minimizes cost without sacrificing quality, and keeps guardrails sharp enough to prevent chaos.

This is where product sense meets **engineering architecture**.

This is where a PM’s thinking can either make an engineering team’s life easier… or a never-ending fire drill.

Let’s unpack the core patterns Miqdad and I use again and again when designing AI systems that actually scale.

![][image8]

### **Pattern 1 \- Cascades and Caches, Not Monoliths**

Most failed AI products share one architectural sin: they treat the model like its everything\!

Every request goes straight to the biggest, most expensive, most powerful model. Every interaction is “one shot.” Every prompt tries to do everything at once.

This works for demos. But at scale? It’s a financial and latency disaster.

The better approach is **cascading**.

Think of your system as a multi-layer orchestra: different instruments playing at different times depending on what’s needed. Miqdad calls this the **Cascade & Cache Strategy**, and it follows a five-stage rhythm:

1. **Detect:** A lightweight classifier or intent detector runs first. It’s fast, cheap, and decides what kind of problem the user is actually bringing. For example, is this a factual query, a creative generation, a structured task, or something unsafe? This step should take milliseconds.  
2. **Retrieve:** Before invoking any model, the system looks up relevant structured data, domain context, or past user interactions. This step creates *boundaries* around the model’s creativity. It makes outputs more relevant and reduces hallucinations.  
3. **Draft:** Instead of jumping to your premium model, you generate a first structure using a **fast, lower-cost model**. The goal here isn’t perfection, it’s speed. Give the system (and sometimes the user) a shape to work with.  
4. **Verify:** Once a draft exists, run targeted checks. Fact checks, schema validation, or narrow verifications that detect obvious nonsense.  
5. **Uplevel:** Only at this point do you invoke a stronger, more expensive model if necessary, for example, to rewrite, refine, or polish critical sections. This is where cost is concentrated *only where it matters*.  
6. **Cache:** If the same type of request or similar inputs appear later, the system doesn’t have to redo everything. It can reuse chunks, reuse embeddings, or reuse structured retrieval results. Caching isn’t just about speed; it’s about survival at scale.

This cascading approach gives you **control over cost, latency, and quality**. It stops you from paying premium dollars for problems that could have been solved with nickels.

And more importantly, it gives your product **predictable performance curves**, something users trust and CFOs love.

### **Pattern 2 \- The Ten Cost Levers That Keep You Alive**

A dirty truth of AI product building: you can design the most brilliant UX and still fail because your token burn rate bleeds you dry.

That’s why Miqdad never builds without knowing his **cost levers** — the ten invisible switches that quietly keep economics in check without compromising quality:

1. **Prompt Compaction:** Shorter, cleaner prompts with fewer redundant tokens.  
2. **Retrieval Scoping:** Don’t give the model the world. Give it exactly what matters.  
3. **Cache Keys:** Reuse outputs when inputs are identical or similar within a tolerance.  
4. **Speculative Decoding:** Start rendering while verifying, to save perceived time.  
5. **Multi-pass Pruning:** Generate once, prune or fix — don’t regenerate endlessly.  
6. **Re-rankers over Re-generators:** When possible, generate fewer options and rerank instead of calling multiple models.  
7. **Post-edit Rules:** Programmatic stylistic cleanup instead of asking the model to redo everything.  
8. **Tiered Model Routing:** Use cheap models for 80% of cases, expensive ones for the hard 20%.  
9. **Batch Verifications:** Group fact checks or safety checks into fewer calls.  
10. **Confidence Threshold Early Exits:** If the system is already confident enough, stop processing.

Each of these levers by itself looks small. But together, they can cut cost-per-outcome by 50–70% *without visibly hurting quality* and sometimes even improving it.

A PM with strong product sense knows when to ask their engineering team to pull these levers.

A PM without it? Just burns money and prays.

### **Pattern 3 \- Guardrail Grammar You Didn’t Know You Needed**

Most AI teams write endless “Do not hallucinate” or “Avoid unsafe outputs” rules in Notion docs or internal wikis. But models don’t read Notion.

Great systems have **Guardrail Grammar**: clear, testable statements that act like circuit breakers.

A few examples:

* **Fact fence:** “Any numerical claim must be linked to a verified source ID.”  
* **Policy fence:** “No irreversible external action (e.g., email, payment) without rung-3 approval.”  
* **Tone fence:** “Must comply with brand lexicon; reject if flagged otherwise.”  
* **Safety fence:** “Refuse and escalate outside domain scope.”

Notice the structure: They’re not vague guidelines. They’re **binary, checkable conditions** that can be enforced at runtime.

This is how you **protect trust without blocking progress**.

And when these guardrails live inside the cascade, not outside of it, they don’t slow you down… they *shape the system*.

Human-in-the-Loop Ladder

One of the most dangerous myths in AI right now is “fully autonomous agents.”

In reality, no system earns autonomy in one leap. It earns it through **progressive delegation**: proving itself at every step.

4 M’s to make sure its alright:

1. **Marking:** Users can flag, correct, or annotate errors.  
2. **Mentoring:** Users can define rules or preferences the system learns.  
3. **Molding:** Users can upload examples or data that shape the model’s behavior.  
4. **Mandating:** Users set non-negotiable constraints the system must obey.

Each rung increases trust, not by asking for it, but by **earning it through structure**.

### **Pattern 4 \- System Design Is Product Sense**

In traditional products, you can separate “what the user experiences” from “how we built it.”

In AI, that separation **doesn’t exist**.

The architecture *directly determines* the user experience in ways that are invisible but unavoidable. Users don’t see your context strategy, but they feel it in every response. They don’t know your cascade exists, but they sense it in the latency. They don’t understand your guardrails, but they notice when trust breaks.

This means a PM who doesn’t understand the system **can’t actually make good product decisions**. When you say “make it faster” without understanding the cascade, your team optimizes the wrong layer. When you say “add more features” without understanding cost surfaces, you ship something economics can’t support.

The best AI PMs think in systems. Not because they’re technical, but because in AI, the system IS the product. Every architectural choice ripples directly into user experience.

You can’t design trust without understanding guardrails. You can’t design speed without understanding cascades. You can’t design quality without understanding context windows.

Product decisions in AI are architectural decisions. If you’re making product calls without understanding the architecture, you’re guessing in the dark.

## **7\. Go-To-Market With Product Sense**

Building an AI product is hard.

But **getting it adopted** is even harder.

And for years, we’ve given this responsibility to product marketers/marketing teams only.

But in AI products, we think product managers should also own this or at least work closely so they understand everything with a deeper lens.

That’s because users don’t think in model architectures. They don’t care about embeddings, routing, or GPT-whatever at ALL.

They care about *whether they can trust the product enough to let it handle something for them*.

And that means your go-to-market strategy has to be **tightly aligned with how your product actually behaves**, not how you wish it would.

![][image9]

### **GTM Concept 1 \- Two-Sided Aha: User and Buyer**

Most launches only design for [one “aha” moment](https://www.news.aakashg.com/p/onboarding-metrics-advanced), usually the demo. The shiny magic trick.

But in AI, you need **two separate aha’s**:

* The **User Aha**: the moment the product makes their life *easier, faster, or safer* in a single interaction.  
* The **Buyer Aha**: the moment the person who controls the budget sees *clear ROI, trust, and defensibility*.

Example:

* A user sees their 30-minute task shrink to 4 minutes → immediate delight.  
* A buyer sees cost per outcome drop by 60% with no new headcount → purchase justified.

Great GTM strategies build both moments deliberately.

### **GTM Concept 2 \- The Golden Path Onboarding**

The first 7 minutes with an AI product are everything.

That’s why you should design **Golden Path [Onboarding](http://google.com/search?q=onboarding+aakash&oq=onboarding+aakash&gs_lcrp=EgZjaHJvbWUqCAgAEEUYJxg7MggIABBFGCcYOzIKCAEQABiiBBiJBTIKCAIQABiABBiiBDIKCAMQABiiBBiJBTIKCAQQABiABBiiBDIHCAUQABjvBTIGCAYQRRg90gEIMTc5NmowajeoAgCwAgA&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8)**:

* One core task.  
* Minimal Golden Context.  
* A Spark moment in under 0.7s.  
* A P80 result within 5 minutes.  
* One visible trust signal (a verified claim, a guardrail, or a confident correction).  
* A sharable artifact at the end (a doc, a clip, a diff \- something users can show).

If the first 7 minutes don’t deliver a “wow” moment that’s **real, not staged**, retention will be brutal. AI products don’t get infinite second chances.

### **GTM Concept 3 \- Sell the Feeling, Not the Feature**

Most AI marketing is a graveyard of vague slogans: “Powered by AI,” “Intelligent workflows,” “Supercharge productivity.”

That doesn’t work.

Because **users don’t buy technology**. They buy the feeling of *relief*… the feeling of “finally, I don’t have to do this myself.”

So instead of selling: “We use GPT-4 for smart summarization,”

You sell: “Turn your 2-hour client report into 7 bullet points in 60 seconds, verified and ready to send.”

Instead of: “AI-powered agent workflows,”

You sell: “The meeting gets scheduled. The follow-up gets written. The calendar gets updated. You don’t lift a finger.”

This is how AI products actually spread: through visceral *moments of utility* that people can remember, repeat, and brag about.

### **GTM Concept 4 \- Trust-Led Distribution**

AI adoption doesn’t scale through feature dumps. It scales through **trust transfers**.

* A manager tells another manager, “I actually let this thing send my team’s recap emails without checking them.”  
* A designer tells another designer, “I actually let it publish drafts straight to the CMS.”  
* A recruiter tells another recruiter, “It pre-qualifies candidates and gets it right.”

That’s distribution gold. And it only happens when your product has real trust architecture underneath it, the kind we discussed in earlier sections.

You can’t fake this with marketing. Trust-led distribution is earned, not bought.

### **GTM Concept 5 \- Strategic Moats in AI GTM**

The hard truth: **anyone can copy your AI feature in a month**.

What they can’t copy is **the moment you own in a user’s workflow**. That’s your moat.

The best AI products don’t win because of better models. They win because they’ve embedded themselves so deeply into a workflow that removing them would break how the user gets their job done.

Think about Grammarly. It’s not in your toolbar. It’s in every text box where you write. Competitors can build better grammar checkers, but they can’t displace the muscle memory of seeing that green circle everywhere.

Your GTM has to answer **one question**: what workflow moment do you own, and why can’t someone else take it from you?

The answer is never “our model is better.” It’s always about trust **earned at a specific edge**, context that compounds with usage, or distribution advantages that snowball over time.

If your GTM sounds like “AI-powered X” or “intelligent Y,” you’re selling a feature *anyone can clone*. If it sounds like “we’re the only ones you trust to do Z automatically,” you’re selling a moat.

### **GTM Concept 6 \- From Demo to Default**

Aim for **default status** as your AI GTM finish line, not viral growth.

The point at which:

* users stop thinking “I’m using this AI tool” and just think “this is how I do my job.”  
* the system disappears into their daily flow.  
* they stop noticing it, because they trust it.

You don’t get to default through aggressive marketing. You get there through compounding product sense.

## **7\. How to Develop Your AI Product Sense**

AI Product Sense isn’t something you’re born with. It’s built through deliberate, repeated practice.

The good news? You can start today with 4 rituals we recommend.

Here’s a presentation on it:

[Developing AI Product Sense](https://www.canva.com/design/DAG1-5ZfX80/jgrNSxijj5fQj20lsiZq-g/view?utm_content=DAG1-5ZfX80&utm_campaign=designshare&utm_medium=link2&utm_source=uniquelinks&utlId=hae0395e989)

#### **Sense Ritual 1 \- Observe AI Products in the Wild (Weekly)**

Stop just *using* AI products. Start *studying* them.

Pick 2-3 AI products each week and use them like a normal person would, but watch with a PM’s eye.

Notice when responses feel inconsistent or when the product seems uncertain. Time the experience from first interaction to final output, and you’ll start recognizing the Spark, Shape, and Seal pattern everywhere.

Try to reverse-engineer the cascade architecture underneath. Ask yourself where context is being pulled in and where guardrails are quietly preventing chaos.

Most importantly, pay attention to trust. When do you feel comfortable letting the system act autonomously? When does that comfort evaporate?

The answers reveal everything.

#### **Sense Ritual 2 \- Deconstruct AI Failures (Monthly)**

Find AI product launches that flopped. Not to mock them, but to learn from them.

Ask the REALM questions:

* **Reality**: Did they misunderstand the actual user need?  
* **Elasticity**: Did the model behavior collapse at scale?  
* **Affordability**: Were the economics unsustainable?  
* **Liability**: Did they lose trust they couldn’t rebuild?  
* **Market**: Was there no compounding advantage?

Every failure is a free lesson in what *not* to do.

#### **Sense Ritual 3 \- Build Your Own Mini-Experiments**

Theory is cheap. Experience is priceless.

Pick a simple AI use case and actually build it. Not a full product, just a small prototype you can ship in a weekend.

Build a basic agent with a few decision points. Add guardrails and watch how they change the experience. Define a Quality Envelope: what’s acceptable at P50, what would delight at P80, and what errors would destroy trust completely.

Then measure your own SUQS metrics: speed, usefulness, quality, and safety. Run small experiments with context length or prompt structure.

The patterns you discover in your own mini-projects will transfer directly to real product decisions.

#### **Sense Ritual 4 \- Learn from People Living It**

AI product development is moving fast. Your product sense only compounds if you’re learning from people at the frontier:

* Attend product reviews where AI features are discussed  
* Read postmortems from AI product teams  
* Study how leaders like Miqdad think through trade-offs  
* Join communities where AI PMs share war stories

The patterns you absorb from great practitioners will save you months of painful mistakes.

#### **The Compounding Effect**

Expect AI Product Sense to compound over time, not improve linearly.

Each time you observe variance in the wild, you pattern-match faster next time.  
Each time you debug a cost blowup, you design better cascades.  
Each time you watch trust break, you build stronger guardrails.

Give it 6 months of deliberate practice, and you’ll be making decisions most PMs can’t see yet.
